<p><b>Maserati</b> (<small>Italian pronunciation:&#160;</small><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Help:IPA_for_Italian" title="Help:IPA for Italian">[mazeˈraːti]</a></span>) is an <a href="/wiki/Italy" title="Italy">Italian</a> <a href="/wiki/Luxury_vehicle" title="Luxury vehicle">luxury vehicle</a> manufacturer established on 1 December 1914, in <a href="/wiki/Bologna" title="Bologna">Bologna</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-maserati.com_3-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-maserati.com-3">[3]</a></sup> The Maserati tagline is "Luxury, sports and style cast in exclusive cars",<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4">[4]</a></sup> and the brand's mission statement is to "Build ultra-luxury performance automobiles with timeless Italian style, accommodating bespoke interiors, and effortless, signature sounding power".<sup id="cite_ref-Maserati_5-year_plan_5-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Maserati_5-year_plan-5">[5]</a></sup></p>
<p>The company's headquarters are now in <a href="/wiki/Modena" title="Modena">Modena</a>, and its emblem is a <a href="/wiki/Trident" title="Trident">trident</a>. It has been owned by the Italian-American car giant <a href="/wiki/Fiat_Chrysler_Automobiles" title="Fiat Chrysler Automobiles">Fiat Chrysler Automobiles</a> (FCA) and FCA's Italian predecessor <a href="/wiki/Fiat_S.p.A." title="Fiat S.p.A.">Fiat S.p.A.</a> since 1993. Maserati was initially associated with <a href="/wiki/Ferrari" title="Ferrari">Ferrari S.p.A.</a>, which was also owned by FCA until being spun off in 2015, but more recently it has become part of the sports car group including <a href="/wiki/Alfa_Romeo" title="Alfa Romeo">Alfa Romeo</a> and <a href="/wiki/Abarth" title="Abarth">Abarth</a> (see section below). In May 2014, due to ambitious plans and product launches, Maserati sold a record of over 3,000 cars. This caused them to increase production of the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Quattroporte" title="Maserati Quattroporte">Quattroporte</a> and <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Ghibli_(M157)" title="Maserati Ghibli (M157)">Ghibli</a> models.<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">[6]</a></sup> In addition to the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Ghibli_(M157)" title="Maserati Ghibli (M157)">Ghibli</a> and <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Quattroporte" title="Maserati Quattroporte">Quattroporte</a>, Maserati offers the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_GranTurismo" title="Maserati GranTurismo">Maserati GranTurismo</a>, the GranTurismo Convertible, and has confirmed that it will be offering the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Levante" title="Maserati Levante">Maserati Levante</a>, the first Maserati SUV, in 2016, and the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Alfieri" title="Maserati Alfieri">Maserati Alfieri</a>, a new 2+2 in 2016.<sup id="cite_ref-autoblog.com_7-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autoblog.com-7">[7]</a></sup> Maserati is placing a production output cap at 75,000 vehicles globally.<sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8">[8]</a></sup></p>

<div style="clear:both;"></div>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="History">History</span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="The_Maserati_brothers">The Maserati brothers</span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">See also: <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Brothers" class="mw-redirect" title="Maserati Brothers">Maserati Brothers</a></div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Four_Maserati_brothers.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7c/Four_Maserati_brothers.jpg/220px-Four_Maserati_brothers.jpg" width="220" height="154" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7c/Four_Maserati_brothers.jpg/330px-Four_Maserati_brothers.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7c/Four_Maserati_brothers.jpg/440px-Four_Maserati_brothers.jpg 2x" data-file-width="600" data-file-height="421" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Four_Maserati_brothers.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Ettore_Maserati" title="Ettore Maserati">Ettore</a>, <a href="/wiki/Bindo_Maserati" title="Bindo Maserati">Bindo</a>, <a href="/wiki/Ernesto_Maserati" title="Ernesto Maserati">Ernesto</a> and <a href="/wiki/Alfieri_Maserati" title="Alfieri Maserati">Alfieri Maserati</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The Maserati brothers, <a href="/wiki/Alfieri_Maserati" title="Alfieri Maserati">Alfieri</a>, <a href="/wiki/Bindo_Maserati" title="Bindo Maserati">Bindo</a>, <a href="/wiki/Carlo_Maserati" title="Carlo Maserati">Carlo</a>, <a href="/wiki/Ettore_Maserati" title="Ettore Maserati">Ettore</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Ernesto_Maserati" title="Ernesto Maserati">Ernesto</a> were all involved with automobiles from the beginning of the 20th century. Alfieri, Bindo and Ernesto built 2-litre Grand Prix cars for <a href="/wiki/Diatto" title="Diatto">Diatto</a>. In 1926, Diatto suspended the production of race cars, leading to the creation of the first Maserati and the founding of the Maserati marque. One of the first Maseratis, driven by Alfieri, won the 1926 <a href="/wiki/Targa_Florio" title="Targa Florio">Targa Florio</a>. Maserati began making race cars with 4, 6, 8 and 16 cylinders (two straight-eights mounted parallel to one another).</p>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:142px;"><a href="/wiki/File:037006698_fontananettuno_bologna_2.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/037006698_fontananettuno_bologna_2.jpg/140px-037006698_fontananettuno_bologna_2.jpg" width="140" height="187" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/037006698_fontananettuno_bologna_2.jpg/210px-037006698_fontananettuno_bologna_2.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/037006698_fontananettuno_bologna_2.jpg/280px-037006698_fontananettuno_bologna_2.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1944" data-file-height="2592" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:037006698_fontananettuno_bologna_2.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Piazza_Maggiore" title="Piazza Maggiore">Piazza Maggiore</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Neptune_(mythology)" title="Neptune (mythology)">Neptune</a> and his trident</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Trident" title="Trident">trident</a> logo of the Maserati car company is based on the <a href="/wiki/Fountain_of_Neptune,_Bologna" title="Fountain of Neptune, Bologna">Fountain of Neptune</a> in <a href="/wiki/Bologna" title="Bologna">Bologna</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Piazza_Maggiore" title="Piazza Maggiore">Piazza Maggiore</a>. In 1920, one of the Maserati brothers, artist Mario, used this symbol in the logo at the suggestion of family friend Marquis Diego de Sterlich. It was considered particularly appropriate for the sports car company due to fact that Neptune represents strength and vigour; additionally the statue is a characteristic symbol of the company's original home city.<sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9">[9]</a></sup></p>
<p>Alfieri Maserati died in 1932, but three other brothers, Bindo, Ernesto and Ettore, kept the firm going, building cars that won races.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Orsi_ownership">Orsi ownership</span></h3>
<p>In 1937, the remaining Maserati brothers sold their shares in the company to the <a href="/wiki/Adolfo_Orsi" title="Adolfo Orsi">Adolfo Orsi</a> family, who in 1940, relocated the company headquarters to their home town of <a href="/wiki/Modena" title="Modena">Modena</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-maserati.com_3-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-maserati.com-3">[3]</a></sup> where it remains to this day. The brothers continued in engineering roles with the company. Racing successes continued, even against the giants of German racing, <a href="/wiki/Audi" title="Audi">Auto Union</a> and <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz" title="Mercedes-Benz">Mercedes</a>. In back-to-back wins in 1939 and 1940, a <a href="/w/index.php?title=Maserati_8CTF&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Maserati 8CTF (page does not exist)">Maserati 8CTF</a> won the <a href="/wiki/Indianapolis_500" title="Indianapolis 500">Indianapolis 500</a>, the only Italian manufacturer ever to do so.</p>
<p>The war then intervened, Maserati abandoned car making to produce components for the Italian war effort. During this time, Maserati worked in fierce competition to construct a V16 <a href="/wiki/Town_car" class="mw-redirect" title="Town car">town car</a> for <a href="/wiki/Benito_Mussolini" title="Benito Mussolini">Benito Mussolini</a> before <a href="/wiki/Ferry_Porsche" class="mw-redirect" title="Ferry Porsche">Ferry Porsche</a> of <a href="/wiki/Volkswagen" title="Volkswagen">Volkswagen</a> built one for <a href="/wiki/Adolf_Hitler" title="Adolf Hitler">Adolf Hitler</a>. This failed, and the plans were scrapped. Once peace was restored, Maserati returned to making cars; the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_A6" title="Maserati A6">Maserati A6</a> series did well in the post-war racing scene.</p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Fangio_%26_Maserati_250F.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a1/Fangio_%26_Maserati_250F.jpg/220px-Fangio_%26_Maserati_250F.jpg" width="220" height="145" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a1/Fangio_%26_Maserati_250F.jpg/330px-Fangio_%26_Maserati_250F.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a1/Fangio_%26_Maserati_250F.jpg/440px-Fangio_%26_Maserati_250F.jpg 2x" data-file-width="709" data-file-height="467" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Fangio_%26_Maserati_250F.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Juan-Manuel_Fangio" class="mw-redirect" title="Juan-Manuel Fangio">Juan-Manuel Fangio</a> driving a <a href="/wiki/Maserati_250F" title="Maserati 250F">Maserati 250F</a>.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Key people joined the Maserati team. <a href="/wiki/Alberto_Massimino" title="Alberto Massimino">Alberto Massimino</a>, an old Fiat engineer, with both Alfa Romeo and Ferrari experiences oversaw the design of all racing models for the next ten years. With him joined engineers <a href="/wiki/Giulio_Alfieri" title="Giulio Alfieri">Giulio Alfieri</a>, <a href="/wiki/Vittorio_Bellentani" title="Vittorio Bellentani">Vittorio Bellentani</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Gioacchino_Colombo" title="Gioacchino Colombo">Gioacchino Colombo</a>. The focus was on the best engines and chassis to succeed in car racing. These new projects saw the last contributions of the Maserati brothers, who after their 10-year contract with Orsi expired went on to form <a href="/wiki/O.S.C.A." title="O.S.C.A.">O.S.C.A.</a>. This new team at Maserati worked on several projects: the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_4CLT" class="mw-redirect" title="Maserati 4CLT">4CLT</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_A6" title="Maserati A6">A6</a> series, the <a href="/w/index.php?title=Maserati_8CLT&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Maserati 8CLT (page does not exist)">8CLT</a>, and, pivotally for the future success of the company, the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_A6GCS" class="mw-redirect" title="Maserati A6GCS">A6GCS</a>.</p>
<p>The famous <a href="/wiki/Argentina" title="Argentina">Argentinian</a> driver <a href="/wiki/Juan-Manuel_Fangio" class="mw-redirect" title="Juan-Manuel Fangio">Juan-Manuel Fangio</a> raced for Maserati for a number of years in the 1950s, producing a number of stunning victories including winning the world championship in 1957 in the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_250F" title="Maserati 250F">Maserati 250F</a> alongside <a href="/wiki/Toulo_de_Graffenried" title="Toulo de Graffenried">Toulo de Graffenried</a>, <a href="/wiki/Louis_Chiron" title="Louis Chiron">Louis Chiron</a>, <a href="/wiki/Prince_Bira" class="mw-redirect" title="Prince Bira">Prince Bira</a>, <a href="/wiki/Enrico_Plat%C3%A9" title="Enrico Platé">Enrico Platé</a>, and a few others. Other racing projects in the 1950s were the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_200S" title="Maserati 200S">200S</a>, <a href="/wiki/Maserati_300S" title="Maserati 300S">300S</a> (with several famous pilots, among them <a href="/wiki/Benoit_Musy" class="mw-redirect" title="Benoit Musy">Benoit Musy</a>), <a href="/wiki/Maserati_350S" title="Maserati 350S">350S</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Maserati_450S" title="Maserati 450S">450S</a>, followed in 1961 by the famous <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Birdcage" class="mw-redirect" title="Maserati Birdcage"><i>Tipo</i> 61</a>.</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Withdrawal_from_racing">Withdrawal from racing</span></h4>
<p>Maserati retired from factory racing participation because of the <i>Guidizzolo tragedy</i><sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10">[a]</a></sup> during the 1957 <a href="/wiki/Mille_Miglia" title="Mille Miglia">Mille Miglia</a>, though they continued to build cars for <a href="/wiki/Privateer_(motorsport)" title="Privateer (motorsport)">privateers</a>. Maserati became more and more focused on building road-going <a href="/wiki/Grand_tourer" title="Grand tourer">grand tourers</a>.</p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:1960_Maserati_3500_GT_coupe_-_white_-_fvr.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/1960_Maserati_3500_GT_coupe_-_white_-_fvr.jpg/220px-1960_Maserati_3500_GT_coupe_-_white_-_fvr.jpg" width="220" height="138" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/1960_Maserati_3500_GT_coupe_-_white_-_fvr.jpg/330px-1960_Maserati_3500_GT_coupe_-_white_-_fvr.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/1960_Maserati_3500_GT_coupe_-_white_-_fvr.jpg/440px-1960_Maserati_3500_GT_coupe_-_white_-_fvr.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1680" data-file-height="1050" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:1960_Maserati_3500_GT_coupe_-_white_-_fvr.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
A 1960 <a href="/wiki/Maserati_3500_GT" title="Maserati 3500 GT">Maserati 3500 GT</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The 1957 <a href="/wiki/Maserati_3500_GT" title="Maserati 3500 GT">Maserati 3500 GT</a> marked a turning point in the marque's history, as its first ground-up <a href="/wiki/Grand_tourer" title="Grand tourer">grand tourer</a> design and first series produced car. Production jumped from a dozen to a few hundreds cars a year. Chief engineer <a href="/wiki/Giulio_Alfieri" title="Giulio Alfieri">Giulio Alfieri</a> took care of the project, and turned the 3.5 L <a href="/wiki/Inline-six_engine" class="mw-redirect" title="Inline-six engine">inline-six engine</a> from the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_350S" title="Maserati 350S">350S</a> into a road engine. First launched with a 2+2 coupé aluminium body over <a href="/wiki/Carrozzeria_Touring" class="mw-redirect" title="Carrozzeria Touring">Carrozzeria Touring</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Superleggera" title="Superleggera">superleggera</a> structure, a steel-bodied short wheelbase <a href="/wiki/Vignale" title="Vignale">Vignale</a> 3500 GT Convertibile <a href="/wiki/Convertible" title="Convertible">open top</a> version followed in 1960. The 3500 GT's success, with over 2200 made, was critical to Maserati's survival in the years that followed the withdrawal from racing.</p>
<p>The 3500 GT also provided the underpinnings for the small-volume V8-engined <a href="/wiki/Maserati_5000_GT" title="Maserati 5000 GT">5000 GT</a>, another seminal car for Maserati. Born from the <a href="/wiki/Mohammad_Reza_Pahlavi" title="Mohammad Reza Pahlavi">Shah of Persia</a>'s whim of owning a road car powered by the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_450S" title="Maserati 450S">Maserati 450S</a> racing engine, it became one of the fastest and most expensive cars of its days. From the third to the thirty-fourth and last example produced it housed Maserati's first ever road-going V8 engine design.</p>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Maserati_Ghibli_green.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/96/Maserati_Ghibli_green.jpg/220px-Maserati_Ghibli_green.jpg" width="220" height="129" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/96/Maserati_Ghibli_green.jpg/330px-Maserati_Ghibli_green.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/96/Maserati_Ghibli_green.jpg/440px-Maserati_Ghibli_green.jpg 2x" data-file-width="4780" data-file-height="2811" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Maserati_Ghibli_green.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
The svelte <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Ghibli" title="Maserati Ghibli">Ghibli</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>In 1962, the 3500 GT was evolved into the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Sebring" title="Maserati Sebring">Sebring</a>, bodied by <a href="/wiki/Vignale" title="Vignale">Vignale</a> and based on the Convertibile short chassis. Next, came the two-seater <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Mistral" title="Maserati Mistral">Mistral</a> coupé in 1963 and Spider in 1964, both six-cylinder powered and designed by <a href="/wiki/Pietro_Frua" title="Pietro Frua">Pietro Frua</a>.</p>
<p>Also in 1963, the company's first <a href="/wiki/Sedan_(automobile)" title="Sedan (automobile)">saloon car</a> arrived, the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Quattroporte" title="Maserati Quattroporte">Maserati Quattroporte</a>, designed by Frua as well. If the 5000 GT inaugurated the marque's first road-going V8, the Quattroporte's <i>Tipo 107</i> 4.2-litre <a href="/wiki/DOHC" class="mw-redirect" title="DOHC">DOHC</a> V8 was the forefather of all Maserati V8s up to 1990.</p>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Ghia" class="mw-redirect" title="Ghia">Ghia</a>-designed <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Ghibli" title="Maserati Ghibli">Ghibli</a> coupé was launched in 1967. It was powered by a 4.7L, <a href="/wiki/Dry_sump" title="Dry sump">dry sump</a> version of Maserati's quad cam V8. The Ghibli Spyder and 4.9-litre Ghibli SS followed.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Citro.C3.ABn_ownership">Citroën ownership</span></h3>
<p>In 1968, Maserati was taken over by French car manufacturer <a href="/wiki/Citro%C3%ABn" title="Citroën">Citroën</a>. Adolfo Orsi remained the nominal president, but Maserati changed a great deal. The relationship with <a href="/wiki/Citro%C3%ABn" title="Citroën">Citroën</a> started as a joint venture, made public in January 1968,<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11">[10]</a></sup> in which Maserati would design and manufacture an engine for an upcoming Citroën flagship car, the <a href="/wiki/Citro%C3%ABn_SM" title="Citroën SM">Citroën SM</a>. Launched in 1970, the SM was a four-seater <a href="/wiki/Front-wheel-drive" class="mw-redirect" title="Front-wheel-drive">front-wheel-drive</a> coupé, powered by a Maserati <i>Tipo C114</i> 2.7 L 90° <a href="/wiki/V6_engine" title="V6 engine">V6 engine</a>. The V6 Maserati engine and its associated gearbox have been used in other vehicles such as Special Rally prepared <a href="/wiki/Citro%C3%ABn_DS" title="Citroën DS">Citroën DS</a>, as used by Bob Neyret in <a href="/wiki/Bandama_Rally" class="mw-redirect" title="Bandama Rally">Bandama Rally</a>, and in the <a href="/wiki/Ligier" title="Ligier">Ligier</a> JS 2.</p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Maserati_Bora_(6086494575).jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/Maserati_Bora_%286086494575%29.jpg/220px-Maserati_Bora_%286086494575%29.jpg" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/Maserati_Bora_%286086494575%29.jpg/330px-Maserati_Bora_%286086494575%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/Maserati_Bora_%286086494575%29.jpg/440px-Maserati_Bora_%286086494575%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1600" data-file-height="1200" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Maserati_Bora_(6086494575).jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Maserati_Bora" title="Maserati Bora">Bora</a>, the first mid-engined Maserati</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>With secure financial backing, new models were launched, and built in much greater numbers than before. Citroën borrowed Maserati expertise and engines for the <a href="/wiki/Citro%C3%ABn_SM" title="Citroën SM">Citroën SM</a> and other vehicles, and Maseratis also incorporated Citroën technology, particularly in <a href="/wiki/Hydropneumatic" class="mw-redirect" title="Hydropneumatic">hydraulics</a>. Engineer <a href="/wiki/Giulio_Alfieri" title="Giulio Alfieri">Giulio Alfieri</a> was key to many of the ambitious designs of this period.</p>
<p>The first new arrival was the 1969 <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Indy" title="Maserati Indy">Maserati Indy</a>—a <a href="/wiki/Vignale" title="Vignale">Vignale</a>-designed four seater GT with a traditional V8 drivetrain, which was produced in over 1100 units.</p>
<p>In 1971, the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Bora" title="Maserati Bora">Maserati Bora</a>, was the first series production <a href="/wiki/Mid-engine_design" title="Mid-engine design">mid-engined</a> Maserati, an idea agreed with Maserati administrator Guy Malleret shortly after the 1968 takeover. The Bora ended Maserati's reputation for producing fast, but technologically out of date cars, being the first Maserati with four wheel <a href="/wiki/Independent_suspension" title="Independent suspension">independent suspension</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">[11]</a></sup> In contrast, competitor Lamborghini had independent suspension in 1964.<sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13">[12]</a></sup></p>
<p>In 1972, fitting a <i>Tipo 114</i> SM-derived V6 enlarged to 3.0-litre into the Bora produced the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Merak" title="Maserati Merak">Maserati Merak</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14">[13]</a></sup></p>
<p>Citroën never developed a 4-door version of the <a href="/wiki/Citro%C3%ABn_SM" title="Citroën SM">Citroën SM</a> - instead Maserati developed the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Quattroporte_II" class="mw-redirect" title="Maserati Quattroporte II">Maserati Quattroporte II</a> that shared most mechanical parts with the SM, including the <a href="/wiki/Mid-engine,_front-wheel-drive_layout" class="mw-redirect" title="Mid-engine, front-wheel-drive layout">mid-engine, front-wheel-drive layout</a>, and six headlight layout.<sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15">[14]</a></sup></p>
<p>To power this large car, Alfieri developed a V8 engine from the SM V6 with 260&#160;PS (190&#160;kW; 260&#160;bhp) and fitted it to a lightly modified SM, proving that the chassis could easily handle the power increase.<sup id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-16">[15]</a></sup> Citroën's and Maserati's financial difficulties hampered the type <a href="/wiki/Homologation" title="Homologation">homologation</a> process; the development costs for the stillborn saloon further aggravated Maserati's situation. Only a dozen Quattroporte IIs were ever produced, all with the V6.</p>
<p>The replacement for the successful Ghibli was the <a href="/wiki/Gruppo_Bertone" title="Gruppo Bertone">Bertone</a>-designed <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Khamsin" title="Maserati Khamsin">Maserati Khamsin</a>, a front-engined grand tourer that introduced in 1972 and produced from 1974; it married the traditional Maserati V8 GT layout with modern <a href="/wiki/Independent_suspension" title="Independent suspension">independent suspension</a>, <a href="/wiki/Unibody" class="mw-redirect" title="Unibody">unibody</a> construction and refined Citroën technologies such as <a href="/wiki/DIRAVI" title="DIRAVI">DIRAVI</a> power steering.</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Crisis_years">Crisis years</span></h4>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Citro%C3%ABn_SM_C114-03_Engine_011.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/92/Citro%C3%ABn_SM_C114-03_Engine_011.jpg/220px-Citro%C3%ABn_SM_C114-03_Engine_011.jpg" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/92/Citro%C3%ABn_SM_C114-03_Engine_011.jpg/330px-Citro%C3%ABn_SM_C114-03_Engine_011.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/92/Citro%C3%ABn_SM_C114-03_Engine_011.jpg/440px-Citro%C3%ABn_SM_C114-03_Engine_011.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1020" data-file-height="680" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Citro%C3%ABn_SM_C114-03_Engine_011.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<i>Tipo C114</i> Maserati V6 in a <a href="/wiki/Citro%C3%ABn_SM" title="Citroën SM">Citroën SM</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Meanwhile, the <a href="/wiki/1973_oil_crisis" title="1973 oil crisis">1973 oil crisis</a> put the brakes on this ambitious expansion; demand for fuel-hungry sports cars shrank drastically. <a href="/wiki/Austerity" title="Austerity">Austerity</a> measures in Italy meant that the domestic market contracted by 60-70%.<sup id="cite_ref-stampa_riconversione_17-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-stampa_riconversione-17">[16]</a></sup> All of the main Italian GT car manufacturers were damaged, having to lay off workers in order to empty lots of unsold cars. Maserati received the hardest blow, as its home market sales accounted for over half of the total—in contrast, for example, with <a href="/wiki/Ferrari" title="Ferrari">Ferrari</a>'s 20%.<sup id="cite_ref-stampa_crisi_1974_18-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-stampa_crisi_1974-18">[17]</a></sup> In this situation, the only Maserati that continued to sell in appreciable numbers was the smaller engined Merak.</p>
<p>In 1974, the <a href="/wiki/1973%E2%80%9375_recession" title="1973–75 recession">1973–75 recession</a> at its climax, things took a turn for the worse. Citroën went bankrupt and its incorporation into <a href="/wiki/PSA_Peugeot_Citro%C3%ABn" class="mw-redirect" title="PSA Peugeot Citroën">PSA Peugeot Citroën</a> begun. The year closed with domestic sales tumbling from 1973's 360 to 150 units,<sup id="cite_ref-stampa_crisi_1974_18-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-stampa_crisi_1974-18">[17]</a></sup> and losses exceeding the <a href="/wiki/Share_capital" title="Share capital">share capital</a>.</p>
<p>On 22 May 1975, a press release from the Citroën management announced all of a sudden that Maserati had been put into <a href="/wiki/Liquidation" title="Liquidation">liquidation</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19">[18]</a></sup> The workforce immediately picketed the factory, but production was not halted. <a href="/wiki/Trade_union" title="Trade union">Trade unions</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Mayor" title="Mayor">mayor</a> of <a href="/wiki/Modena" title="Modena">Modena</a> and local politicians mobilised to save the 800 jobs; <a href="/wiki/Industry_minister" title="Industry minister">industry minister</a> <a href="/wiki/Carlo_Donat-Cattin" title="Carlo Donat-Cattin">Carlo Donat-Cattin</a> even flew to Paris to meet Citroën chairman <a href="/wiki/Francois_Rollier" title="Francois Rollier">Francois Rollier</a>. An agreement was reached in June,<sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-20">[19]</a></sup> after several meetings and assemblies. During one of these meetings, Citroën liquidators disclosed that a possible Italian buyer had showed up, and the name of de Tomaso was put forth for the first time.<sup id="cite_ref-21" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-21">[20]</a></sup> Citroën accepted to suspend liquidation as requested by the Italian government, which on its part guaranteed six months of <a href="/wiki/Unemployment_benefits_in_Italy#Redundancy_fund" title="Unemployment benefits in Italy">special redundancy fund</a> to pay the salaries.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="De_Tomaso_era">De Tomaso era</span></h3>
<p>On 8 August 1975, an agreement was signed at the Ministry of Industry in Rome, and property of Maserati passed from Citroën to Italian state-owned <a href="/wiki/Holding_company" title="Holding company">holding company</a> <a href="/w/index.php?title=GEPI&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="GEPI (page does not exist)">GEPI</a><sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22">[b]</a></sup> and <a href="/wiki/Alejandro_de_Tomaso" title="Alejandro de Tomaso">Alejandro de Tomaso</a>, an <a href="/wiki/Argentina" title="Argentina">Argentinian</a> <a href="/wiki/Business_magnate" title="Business magnate">industrialist</a> and former <a href="/wiki/Racing_driver" class="mw-redirect" title="Racing driver">racing driver</a>, who became <a href="/wiki/President_(corporate_title)" title="President (corporate title)">president</a> and <a href="/wiki/Chief_executive_officer" title="Chief executive officer">CEO</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23">[21]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-edition.cnn.com_24-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-edition.cnn.com-24">[22]</a></sup> As of December 1979, GEPI's quota amounted to 88.75% of Maserati,<sup id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25">[23]</a></sup> the remaining 11.25% being controlled by De Tomaso through an holding which grouped his automotive interests in Maserati and <a href="/wiki/Innocenti" title="Innocenti">Innocenti</a>. Beginning in 1976, new models were introduced, sharing their underpinnings—but not their engines—with <a href="/wiki/De_Tomaso" title="De Tomaso">De Tomaso</a> cars; first came the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Kyalami" title="Maserati Kyalami">Kyalami</a> grand tourer, derived from the <a href="/wiki/De_Tomaso_Longchamp" title="De Tomaso Longchamp">De Tomaso Longchamp</a> restyled by <a href="/wiki/Pietro_Frua" title="Pietro Frua">Frua</a> and powered by Maserati's V8. Following was the <a href="/wiki/Italdesign_Giugiaro" title="Italdesign Giugiaro">Italdesign Giugiaro</a>-designed <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Quattroporte#Quattroporte_III" title="Maserati Quattroporte">third generation Quattroporte</a>, introduced in 1976 and put on sale in 1979. Bora sales dwindled down; Khamsin was discontinued between 1982 and 1983. Progressively stripped of its Citroën-derived parts, the Merak continued to sell over one hundred pieces a year, until 1982.</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="The_Biturbo">The Biturbo</span></h4>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:1985_Maserati_Biturbo_E,_front_left_(US).jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/45/1985_Maserati_Biturbo_E%2C_front_left_%28US%29.jpg/220px-1985_Maserati_Biturbo_E%2C_front_left_%28US%29.jpg" width="220" height="119" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/45/1985_Maserati_Biturbo_E%2C_front_left_%28US%29.jpg/330px-1985_Maserati_Biturbo_E%2C_front_left_%28US%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/45/1985_Maserati_Biturbo_E%2C_front_left_%28US%29.jpg/440px-1985_Maserati_Biturbo_E%2C_front_left_%28US%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="5388" data-file-height="2924" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:1985_Maserati_Biturbo_E,_front_left_(US).jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
A 1985 <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Biturbo" title="Maserati Biturbo">Maserati Biturbo</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The 1980s saw the company largely abandoning the mid-engined sports car in favour of a compact <a href="/wiki/Front-engine_design" class="mw-redirect" title="Front-engine design">front-engined</a>, <a href="/wiki/Rear-wheel_drive" class="mw-redirect" title="Rear-wheel drive">rear-drive</a> <a href="/wiki/Coup%C3%A9" title="Coupé">coupé</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Biturbo" title="Maserati Biturbo">Maserati Biturbo</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-26">[24]</a></sup> Of fairly conventional construction, the Biturbo's pleasure and pain was its <a href="/wiki/Twin-turbo" title="Twin-turbo">twin-turbocharged</a> <a href="/wiki/V6_engine" title="V6 engine">V6 engine</a>, the <a href="/wiki/List_of_automotive_superlatives" title="List of automotive superlatives">first ever in a production car</a>. This engine, descending from Alfieri's 90° V6, was fitted in a large number of models, all sharing key components; every new Maserati launched up to the 1990s would derive from the Biturbo. The Biturbo family was extremely successful at exploiting the <a href="/wiki/Aspirational_brand" title="Aspirational brand">aspirational image</a> of the <i>Maserati</i> name—selling 40,000 units.</p>
<p>In 1983 and 1984, the range was extended to include <a href="/wiki/Sedan_(car)" class="mw-redirect" title="Sedan (car)">saloons</a> (the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Biturbo#420_and_425" title="Maserati Biturbo">425 and 420</a>) and a <a href="/wiki/Cabriolet" class="mw-redirect" title="Cabriolet">cabriolet</a> (the <a href="/wiki/Zagato" title="Zagato">Zagato</a>-bodied <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Biturbo#The_Spyders" title="Maserati Biturbo">Spyder</a>), respectively on a long and short wheelbase Biturbo platform.</p>
<p>During 1984, <a href="/wiki/Chrysler" title="Chrysler">Chrysler</a> bought a 5% share in the new company. Following an agreement between De Tomaso's friend and Chrysler head <a href="/wiki/Lee_Iacocca" title="Lee Iacocca">Lee Iacocca</a>, a <a href="/wiki/Joint_venture" title="Joint venture">joint venture</a> was signed. Maserati would produce a car for export to the American market, the <a href="/wiki/Chrysler_TC_by_Maserati" title="Chrysler TC by Maserati">Chrysler TC by Maserati</a>, with Chrysler-sourced engines. In July of that same year, a <a href="/wiki/Merger" class="mw-redirect" title="Merger">merger</a> between Maserati and Nuova Innocenti was decided; it was carried out in 1985.<sup id="cite_ref-27" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-27">[25]</a></sup> Chrysler upped its stake to 15.6% by underwriting three quarters of a 75 billion <a href="/wiki/Italian_Lira" class="mw-redirect" title="Italian Lira">Lire</a> capital raise in 1986.<sup id="cite_ref-28" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-28">[26]</a></sup></p>
<p>New Biturbo-based cars and model evolutions were launched year after year. In 1984, it was the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Biturbo#228" title="Maserati Biturbo">228</a>, a large coupé built on the long wheelbase saloon chassis, with a new 2.8 L version of the twin-turbo V6. <a href="/wiki/Weber_carburetors" class="mw-redirect" title="Weber carburetors">Weber</a> <a href="/wiki/Fuel_injection" title="Fuel injection">Fuel injection</a> was phased in starting in 1986, bringing improved reliability and a host of new model variants. The same year, the ageing third generation Quattroporte was updated as the luxurious <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Quattroporte#Royale" title="Maserati Quattroporte">Maserati Royale</a>, built to order in an handful of examples a year; its discontinuation in 1990 marked the disappearance of Maserati's four-cam V8 engine, a design that could trace its roots back to the 450S racer and the legendary 5000 GT. In 1987, the 2.8-litre <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Biturbo#430" title="Maserati Biturbo">430</a> topped the saloon range. 1988 brought the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Karif" title="Maserati Karif">Maserati Karif</a> 2.8-litre two-seater, based on the short wheelbase Spyder chassis. Meanwhile, the Biturbo name was dropped altogether, as updated coupés and saloons were updated became the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Biturbo#222" title="Maserati Biturbo">222</a> and <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Biturbo#422" title="Maserati Biturbo">422</a>. 1989 marked the reintroduction of an eight-cylinder grand tourer: the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Shamal" title="Maserati Shamal">Maserati Shamal</a>, built on a modified short wheelbase Biturbo bodyshell, clad in new muscular bodywork by <a href="/wiki/Marcello_Gandini" title="Marcello Gandini">Marcello Gandini</a>. It was powered by an all-new twin-turbo 32-valve V8 engine paired to a 6-speed gearbox. Two-litre, 24-valve engines also debuted.</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="De_Tomaso-Fiat_years">De Tomaso-Fiat years</span></h4>
<p>In October 1989, De Tomaso bought the remaining Gepi quota. In December, <a href="/wiki/Fiat_S.p.A." title="Fiat S.p.A.">Fiat</a> entered in Maserati's history. Maserati and Innocenti were separated; Innocenti Milano S.p.A., the company that sold Innocenti cars, continued its business under a 51% Fiat Auto ownership. All of the <a href="/wiki/Modena" title="Modena">Modena</a> and <a href="/wiki/Lambrate" title="Lambrate">Lambrate</a> plants went to a newly created company, the still extant Maserati S.p.A.; 49% of it was owned by Fiat Auto and 51% was controlled by De Tomaso through the old company, Officine Alfieri Maserati.<sup id="cite_ref-stampa_fiat89_29-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-stampa_fiat89-29">[27]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-repubblica_fiat89_30-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-repubblica_fiat89-30">[28]</a></sup></p>
<p>In the early Nineties, a <a href="/wiki/Mid-engined" class="mw-redirect" title="Mid-engined">mid-engined</a> sports car was developed, the <a href="/w/index.php?title=Maserati_Chubasco&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Maserati Chubasco (page does not exist)">Maserati Chubasco</a>—which was to début in 1992. It featured Gandini-designed body, a V8 powertrain and a <a href="/wiki/Backbone_chassis" title="Backbone chassis">backbone chassis</a>. The project was cancelled, as it proved too expensive. Starting in 1990, the entire range received a facelift by Marcello Gandini, on the lines of the Shamal's styling. The last version of the Biturbo coupé proper was called <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Biturbo#Racing" title="Maserati Biturbo">Maserati Racing</a>. It was a transitional model in which several features to be found on the upcoming Ghibli were tested.</p>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Ghibli#Ghibli_II" title="Maserati Ghibli">Maserati Ghibli</a> was introduced in 1992. It was a six-cylinder coupé, with modified Biturbo underpinnings dressed by new Gandini bodywork (toned down from the Shamal) and the latest evolution of the 24-valve twin-turbo V6 with record breaking specific output. The underpinnings of the stillborn Chubasco gave birth to the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Barchetta" title="Maserati Barchetta">Maserati Barchetta</a>, a small open top mid-engine sports car styled by Synthesis Design (Carlo Gaino).<sup id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-31">[29]</a></sup> A <a href="/wiki/Auto_racing#One-make_racing" title="Auto racing">one-make racing series</a> was held in 1992 and 1993, using the Barchetta Corsa racing version; the road-going Barchetta Stradale was never put into production. Just 17 Barchetta examples were produced. Between 1992 and 1994 all models save for the Ghibli and Shamal were progressively discontinued.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Fiat_ownership">Fiat ownership</span></h3>
<p>On 19 May 1993, 17 years after having rescued it from liquidation, Alejandro De Tomaso sold its 51% stake in Maserati to Fiat, which became the sole owner.<sup id="cite_ref-edition.cnn.com_24-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-edition.cnn.com-24">[22]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-32">[30]</a></sup> Substantial investments were made in Maserati, and it has since undergone something of a renaissance.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (January 2014)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup></p>
<p>In 1998, a new chapter began in Maserati's history when the company launched the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_3200_GT" title="Maserati 3200 GT">3200 GT</a>. This two-door coupé is powered by a 3.2&#160;L twin-turbocharged V8 derived from the Shamal engine, which produces 370&#160;hp (276&#160;kW).</p>
<p>Over two decades after the ill-fated <a href="/wiki/Chrysler_TC_by_Maserati" title="Chrysler TC by Maserati">Chrysler TC by Maserati</a> during Chrysler's brief ownership stake in Maserati, the two companies became interconnected again when <a href="/wiki/Fiat" class="mw-redirect" title="Fiat">Fiat</a> purchased majority control of Chrysler in 2011 as a result of <a href="/wiki/Chrysler_Chapter_11_reorganization" title="Chrysler Chapter 11 reorganization">Chrysler's bankruptcy</a>.</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Ferrari">Ferrari</span></h4>
<p>In July 1997, <a href="/wiki/Fiat" class="mw-redirect" title="Fiat">Fiat</a> sold a 50% share in the company to Maserati's long-time arch-rival <a href="/wiki/Ferrari" title="Ferrari">Ferrari</a> (Ferrari itself being owned by <a href="/wiki/Fiat" class="mw-redirect" title="Fiat">Fiat</a>).<sup id="cite_ref-maserati.com_3-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-maserati.com-3">[3]</a></sup> In 1999, Ferrari took full control, making Maserati its luxury division. A new factory was built, replacing the existing 1940s-vintage facility. Ferrari is credited for bringing Maserati back into business, after many lacklustre years of Maserati teetering on the brink of <a href="/wiki/Bankruptcy" title="Bankruptcy">bankruptcy</a>.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (February 2014)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup></p>
<p>The last links to the de Tomaso era were cut in 2002, when the 3200 GT was replaced by the Maserati <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Coup%C3%A9" title="Maserati Coupé">Coupé</a> and <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Coup%C3%A9" title="Maserati Coupé">Spyder</a>; evolved from the 3200, these cars ditched its twin-turbocharged V8 for an all-new, <a href="/wiki/Naturally_aspirated" class="mw-redirect" title="Naturally aspirated">naturally aspirated</a>, <a href="/wiki/Dry_sump" title="Dry sump">dry sump</a> 4.2-litre V8 with a <a href="/wiki/Transaxle" title="Transaxle">transaxle</a> gearbox. In turn Coupé and Spyder were replaced by the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_GranTurismo" title="Maserati GranTurismo">GranTurismo and GranCabrio</a>.</p>
<p>Meanwhile, two new models have been shown to the public: the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_MC12" title="Maserati MC12">MC12</a> road supersports and successful GT racer with a <a href="/wiki/Enzo_Ferrari_(automobile)" title="Enzo Ferrari (automobile)">Ferrari Enzo</a>–derived chassis and engine and the new <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Quattroporte" title="Maserati Quattroporte">Quattroporte</a>, a high luxury <a href="/wiki/Sedan_(car)" class="mw-redirect" title="Sedan (car)">saloon</a> with the 4.2l V8 engine.<sup id="cite_ref-33" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-33">[31]</a></sup> Nowadays, Maserati is back in business and successfully selling on a global basis. In 2001, Ferrari decided to throw away all the old tooling and installed high-tech devices in the Modena factory, making it one of the most advanced in the world.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (February 2014)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup></p>
<p>Since early 2002, Maserati once again entered the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a> market,<sup id="cite_ref-usatoday.com_34-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-usatoday.com-34">[32]</a></sup> which has quickly become for Maserati the largest market worldwide. The company has also re-entered the racing arena with their Trofeo and, in December 2003, the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_MC12" title="Maserati MC12">Maserati MC12</a> (formerly known as the MCC), which was developed according to FIA GT regulations and has since competed with great success in the world FIA GT championship, winning the teams championship three consecutive times from 2005 to 2007. The MC12 has also been raced in various national GT championship as well as in the American Le Mans series. The MC12 is based on the <a href="/wiki/Enzo_Ferrari_(car)" class="mw-redirect" title="Enzo Ferrari (car)">Enzo Ferrari</a> sports car;<sup id="cite_ref-worldcarfans.com_35-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-worldcarfans.com-35">[33]</a></sup> 50 street-legal homologation models (roadsters and coupés) have been sold for about <a href="/wiki/United_States_dollar" title="United States dollar">US$</a>700,000 each.</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="The_Maserati_and_Alfa_Romeo_Group_under_Fiat_Group">The Maserati and Alfa Romeo Group under Fiat Group</span></h4>
<p>The Maserati and <a href="/wiki/Alfa_Romeo" title="Alfa Romeo">Alfa Romeo</a> group, under <a href="/wiki/Fiat" class="mw-redirect" title="Fiat">Fiat Group</a>, started in 2005, when Maserati was split off from Ferrari and partnered with Alfa Romeo.<sup id="cite_ref-carkeys.co.uk_36-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-carkeys.co.uk-36">[34]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-automobile.com_37-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-automobile.com-37">[35]</a></sup> On 9 June 2005 the 20,000th Maserati, a <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Quattroporte#Quattroporte_V" title="Maserati Quattroporte">Quattroporte</a>, left the factory.<sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38">[36]</a></sup> In the second quarter of 2007, Maserati made profit for the first time in 17 years under <a href="/wiki/Fiat" class="mw-redirect" title="Fiat">Fiat</a> ownership.<sup id="cite_ref-italiaspeed.com_39-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-italiaspeed.com-39">[37]</a></sup></p>
<p>On January 22, 2010, <a href="/wiki/Fiat" class="mw-redirect" title="Fiat">Fiat</a> announced that it had created a new partnership/brand group for Alfa Romeo, Maserati, and Abarth. The group was led by Harald J. Wester, the current CEO of Maserati. <a href="/wiki/Sergio_Marchionne" title="Sergio Marchionne">Sergio Marchionne</a> said that "[the] purpose of bringing the Alfa Romeo, Maserati and Abarth brands under the same leadership is to emphasize and leverage the value of the shared qualities of the three brands in terms of their sporting characteristics and performance." <sup id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-40">[38]</a></sup> Abarth stayed under Wester's leadership until 2013, leaving Maserati and Alfa Romeo in the brand group, led by Wester.<sup id="cite_ref-fcagroup.com_41-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-fcagroup.com-41">[39]</a></sup> Although Maserati and Alfa Romeo are in a brand group, Alfa Romeo is structured under FCA Italy S.p.A., which itself is structured under FCA, whereas Maserati is structured solely under FCA. In addition, in an interview with Wester in 2015, he clarified that his "role at Maserati is different from that in the Alfa Romeo as the latter is better integrated into the Fiat Group" and that "the new Alfa car won't share any parts with the current Maserati model. I'm not planning any technical merging of these two makes."<sup id="cite_ref-:0_42-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-42">[40]</a></sup></p>
<p>In 2013, Maserati started its expansion with the sixth-generation <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Quattroporte" title="Maserati Quattroporte">Maserati Quattroporte</a>, which was designed to better compete with the <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_S-Class" title="Mercedes-Benz S-Class">Mercedes-Benz S-Class</a>. This was followed by the introduction of the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Ghibli_(M157)" title="Maserati Ghibli (M157)">Ghibli</a>, which was slated to compete against the <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_E-Class" title="Mercedes-Benz E-Class">Mercedes-Benz E-Class</a> and <a href="/wiki/BMW_5-series" class="mw-redirect" title="BMW 5-series">BMW 5-series</a>. On May 6, 2014, Maserati confirmed production of the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Levante" title="Maserati Levante">Levante</a> SUV and the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Alfieri" title="Maserati Alfieri">Alfieri</a> (previously a 2+2 concept sports car that was named after Alfieri Maserati).<sup id="cite_ref-autoblog.com_7-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autoblog.com-7">[7]</a></sup> At this event, it was revealed that 2014 will be the last year of production for the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_GranTurismo" title="Maserati GranTurismo">GranTurismo</a> and GranTurismo Convertible,<sup id="cite_ref-autoblog.com_7-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autoblog.com-7">[7]</a></sup> although production of the GranTurismo was extended until 2016, with a new GranTurismo still being unveiled in 2018.<sup id="cite_ref-autoblog.com_7-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autoblog.com-7">[7]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-43" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-43">[41]</a></sup> In a 2015 interview, Harald J. Wester said that there was room for a future sports car, positioned above the Alfieri.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_42-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-42">[40]</a></sup></p>
<p>Along with their expansion, Maserati started their re-entrance into the high-performance car field, in order to compete with brands such as <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-AMG" title="Mercedes-AMG">Mercedes-AMG</a>, <a href="/wiki/BMW_M" title="BMW M">BMW M</a>, <a href="/wiki/Porsche" title="Porsche">Porsche</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jaguar_Cars" title="Jaguar Cars">Jaguar</a>, and in certain cases, <a href="/wiki/Ferrari" title="Ferrari">Ferrari</a>. This is being done with Maseratis that have higher output engines, higher performance components, and better handling. The fastest <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Alfieri" title="Maserati Alfieri">Maserati Alfieri</a> will be receiving a 520&#160;bhp (388&#160;kW; 527&#160;PS) V6 with all-wheel drive, while the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Quattroporte" title="Maserati Quattroporte">Quattroporte</a>, <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Ghibli_(M157)" title="Maserati Ghibli (M157)">Ghibli</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Levante" title="Maserati Levante">Levante</a> are receiving 560&#160;bhp (418&#160;kW; 568&#160;PS) V8s in the future with all-wheel drive, in order to better compete with their respective <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-AMG" title="Mercedes-AMG">AMGs</a>, <a href="/wiki/BMW_M" title="BMW M">M cars</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jaguars" class="mw-redirect" title="Jaguars">Jaguars</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Porsche" title="Porsche">Porsches</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Maserati_5-year_plan_5-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Maserati_5-year_plan-5">[5]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-44" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-44">[42]</a></sup> The Maserati Alfieri will be competitive against the <a href="/wiki/Mercedes-AMG_GT" title="Mercedes-AMG GT">Mercedes-AMG GT</a>, <a href="/wiki/Porsche_911" title="Porsche 911">Porsche 911</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jaguar_F-Type" title="Jaguar F-Type">Jaguar F-Type R</a>, and even the <a href="/wiki/Ferrari_California_T" class="mw-redirect" title="Ferrari California T">Ferrari California T</a> in terms of performance. The replacement for the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_GranTurismo" title="Maserati GranTurismo">GranTurismo</a>, to be presented in 2018, will have a 560&#160;bhp (418&#160;kW; 568&#160;PS) V8.<sup id="cite_ref-Maserati_5-year_plan_5-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Maserati_5-year_plan-5">[5]</a></sup> The high performance all wheel drive version of the Ghibli (as mentioned above) will likely wear a GTS badge. For the Quattroporte, this will be a replacement for the GTS version (with increased power and all wheel drive, as mentioned above).</p>
<p>In addition, Harald J. Wester stated that Maserati is experimenting with plug-in hybrid powertrains, and that one will be offered in the second half of 2017 in the Levante SUV.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_42-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-42">[40]</a></sup> By 2018, the base Ghibli will receive a performance upgrade 350&#160;bhp (261&#160;kW; 355&#160;PS), and the Ghibli S Q4 to 450&#160;bhp (336&#160;kW; 456&#160;PS).<sup id="cite_ref-Maserati_5-year_plan_5-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Maserati_5-year_plan-5">[5]</a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:100_Years_Maserati_at_Autoworld_Brussels.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/ba/100_Years_Maserati_at_Autoworld_Brussels.JPG/220px-100_Years_Maserati_at_Autoworld_Brussels.JPG" width="220" height="82" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/ba/100_Years_Maserati_at_Autoworld_Brussels.JPG/330px-100_Years_Maserati_at_Autoworld_Brussels.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/ba/100_Years_Maserati_at_Autoworld_Brussels.JPG/440px-100_Years_Maserati_at_Autoworld_Brussels.JPG 2x" data-file-width="2839" data-file-height="1061" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:100_Years_Maserati_at_Autoworld_Brussels.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
The 2014 Maserati lineup, as shown at the 100th Year Anniversary in <a href="/wiki/AutoWorld_(museum)" class="mw-redirect" title="AutoWorld (museum)">Autoworld Brussels</a> From left to right: Maserati GranCabrio Sport, Maserati Ghibli III and Maserati Quattroporte Series VI</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Maserati sales in 2013 were 15,400 units, which is up from just over 6,000 units worldwide in 2012 (2013 included the release of the new Quattroporte and Ghibli towards the end of the year, and thus the first year to fully represent the sales inclusive of these models is 2014).<sup id="cite_ref-autoblog.com_7-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autoblog.com-7">[7]</a></sup> In May, 2014, Maserati sold a company record of over 3,000 cars worldwide, causing them to increase production of the Ghibli and Quattroporte.<sup id="cite_ref-45" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-45">[43]</a></sup> For that same month in the United States, Maserati sold 1,114 vehicles, which is up 406.19% over the same month in the previous year in the United States.<sup id="cite_ref-46" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-46">[44]</a></sup> Maserati's best month of sales in the United States was September 2014, with 1,318 units sold.<sup id="cite_ref-autoblog.com_10.2F14_47-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autoblog.com_10.2F14-47">[45]</a></sup> The month in 2014 where the increase on sales for the same month of the previous year was the highest was May, with a volume increase of 406.19%.<sup id="cite_ref-autoblog.com_10.2F14_47-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autoblog.com_10.2F14-47">[45]</a></sup> The sales target for 2018 is 75,000 units worldwide.<sup id="cite_ref-autoblog.com_7-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autoblog.com-7">[7]</a></sup></p>
<p>2014 marked an historic record of 13,411 total units sold in North America for the year, a 169% increase versus 2013, boasting the highest-ever overall sales year for Maserati North America, Inc.<sup id="cite_ref-48" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-48">[46]</a></sup> Worldwide, in 2014 Maserati sold about 36,500 cars, a 136% increase over 2013.<sup id="cite_ref-49" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-49">[47]</a></sup> Harald J. Wester stated that Maserati will not surpass the 70,000 sales per year mark, and that Maserati will maintain its current position in the higher end of the luxury sports car market, not expanding downmarket and making vehicles smaller and less expensive than the Ghibli and Levante (such as those similar to the Audi Q5 and Mercedes-Benz C-Class), as other FCA brands, specifically Alfa Romeo, are or will be in those market spaces.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_42-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-42">[40]</a></sup></p>
<p>Since 2009, <a href="/wiki/Marco_Tencone" title="Marco Tencone">Marco Tencone</a> (born 1967) has been the head designer of Maserati cars.</p>

<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Maserati_Quattroporte">Maserati Quattroporte</span></h4>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Quattroporte" title="Maserati Quattroporte">Maserati Quattroporte</a></div>
<p>Italian for "four-door," the Maserati Quattroporte is a <a href="/wiki/Sports_car" title="Sports car">sporting</a> <a href="/wiki/Luxury_car" class="mw-redirect" title="Luxury car">luxury saloon</a>. The sixth generation Maserati Quattroporte was introduced in 2013. The Quattroporte is currently available in S Q4, GTS and Diesel trim. The S Q4 has an advanced four wheel drive system, and a 404-horsepower twin-turbo V6.<sup id="cite_ref-50" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-50">[48]</a></sup> The GTS is rear wheel drive, and has a 523-horsepower V8.<sup id="cite_ref-51" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-51">[49]</a></sup> A Quattroporte Diesel model is offered on selected markets, making 275 horsepower (250&#160;hp in Italy) and 442&#160;ft-lbs of torque. The sixth-generation Quattroporte has grown in size in order to better compete with the roomier luxury saloons like the Mercedes-Benz S-Class.<sup id="cite_ref-52" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-52">[50]</a></sup></p>
<p>By 2018, the Quattroporte S Q4 will be upgraded to produce 450&#160;bhp (336&#160;kW; 456&#160;PS) from its V6, and the GTS to produce 560&#160;bhp (418&#160;kW; 568&#160;PS) horsepower from its V8, both with all-wheel drive (for the V8 to increase performance).<sup id="cite_ref-Maserati_5-year_plan2_53-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Maserati_5-year_plan2-53">[51]</a></sup></p>
<div style="clear:both;"></div>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Maserati_Ghibli">Maserati Ghibli</span></h4>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Ghibli_(M157)" title="Maserati Ghibli (M157)">Maserati Ghibli (M157)</a></div>
<p>The first presentation of this car was on 20 April 2013 in <a href="/wiki/Shanghai" title="Shanghai">Shanghai</a>. It is a sporting/luxury <a href="/wiki/Executive_car" title="Executive car">executive saloon</a> that competes against the BMW 5 Series, Mercedes E-Class or Audi A6. This new model is expected to be key in order to reach the ambitious target sales of 50,000 cars a year by 2015, and 75,000 by 2018. The car, along with the new Quattroporte, is built in the Italian factory of <a href="/wiki/Grugliasco" title="Grugliasco">Grugliasco</a>, <a href="/wiki/Turin" title="Turin">Turin</a> (former <a href="/wiki/Gruppo_Bertone" title="Gruppo Bertone">Bertone</a>). The base Ghibli comes with 330 horsepower, the Ghibli Diesel with 275 horsepower (also 250 in Italy only), and the Ghibli S Q4 with 410 horsepower. By 2018, the base Ghibli will have 350 horsepower, the S Q4 450 horsepower, and a higher performance version (likely GTS) which will have 560&#160;bhp (418&#160;kW; 568&#160;PS) and all-wheel drive.<sup id="cite_ref-Maserati_5-year_plan_5-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Maserati_5-year_plan-5">[5]</a></sup></p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Maserati_GranTurismo_and_GranCabrio">Maserati GranTurismo and GranCabrio</span></h4>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Maserati_GranTurismo" title="Maserati GranTurismo">Maserati GranTurismo</a></div>
<p>The Maserati GranTurismo is a <a href="/wiki/Grand_tourer" title="Grand tourer">grand tourer</a> introduced in 2007. The GranTurismo has a 4.7-litre V8, making 454&#160;bhp (339&#160;kW; 460&#160;PS) in Sport form and MC form. A convertible (GranCabrio) version is also available in standard, Sport, and MC form. The final production year for the Maserati GranTurismo is scheduled to be 2014, but it will be revived in 2018 with a 560&#160;bhp (418&#160;kW; 568&#160;PS) V8, again in rear wheel drive form.<sup id="cite_ref-autoblog.com_7-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autoblog.com-7">[7]</a></sup></p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Maserati_Levante">Maserati Levante</span></h4>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Levante" title="Maserati Levante">Maserati Levante</a></div>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Levante" title="Maserati Levante">Maserati Levante</a> is a <a href="/wiki/Crossover_SUV" class="mw-redirect" title="Crossover SUV">crossover SUV</a> due to be released in 2014. It has been anticipated with the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Kubang" title="Maserati Kubang">Maserati Kubang</a> concept SUV in September 2003 at the <a href="/wiki/Frankfurt_Motor_Show" class="mw-redirect" title="Frankfurt Motor Show">Frankfurt Motor Show</a> and again in 2011. It was announced, at the Paris Motor Show held in Paris in September 2012. The Levante will be assembled in Mirafiori Plant, in <a href="/wiki/Turin" title="Turin">Turin</a>. It was confirmed on May 6, 2014.<sup id="cite_ref-autoblog.com_7-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autoblog.com-7">[7]</a></sup> The Levante 3.0L V6 will be offered in either 350 or 425 horsepower states of tune, with a 3.8L V8 producing 560&#160;bhp (418&#160;kW; 568&#160;PS) down the road, due in 2018. All models will have all-wheel drive.<sup id="cite_ref-Maserati_5-year_plan_5-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Maserati_5-year_plan-5">[5]</a></sup></p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Maserati_Alfieri">Maserati Alfieri</span></h4>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Alfieri" title="Maserati Alfieri">Maserati Alfieri</a></div>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Maserati_Alfieri" title="Maserati Alfieri">Maserati Alfieri</a> was a concept 2+2 presented at the Geneva Motor Show in 2014. The concept was based off the lighter chassis of the <a href="/wiki/Maserati_GranTurismo" title="Maserati GranTurismo">GranTurismo MC Stradale</a>, although it had a shorter wheelbase. The concept was introduced with a 4.7 liter V8 producing 460&#160;bhp (343&#160;kW; 466&#160;PS).</p>
<p>The Alfieri was confirmed for production in 2016 at a <a href="/wiki/Fiat_Chrysler_Automobiles" title="Fiat Chrysler Automobiles">Fiat Chrysler Automobiles</a> event on May 6, 2014.<sup id="cite_ref-autoblog.com_7-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autoblog.com-7">[7]</a></sup> The production version will receive three different V6 engine choices, producing 410&#160;bhp (306&#160;kW; 416&#160;PS), 450&#160;bhp (336&#160;kW; 456&#160;PS), and 520&#160;bhp (388&#160;kW; 527&#160;PS), respectively.<sup id="cite_ref-autoblog.com_7-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autoblog.com-7">[7]</a></sup> The 450 horsepower and 520 horsepower versions will only have an all-wheel drive system. The Alfieri will be joined by an Alfieri convertible in 2017.<sup id="cite_ref-autoblog.com_7-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autoblog.com-7">[7]</a></sup></p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Motorsport">Motorsport</span></h2>
<table class="plainlinks metadata ambox mbox-small-left ambox-content" role="presentation">
<tr>
<td class="mbox-image"><a href="/wiki/File:Wiki_letter_w_cropped.svg" class="image"><img alt="[icon]" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Wiki_letter_w_cropped.svg/20px-Wiki_letter_w_cropped.svg.png" width="20" height="14" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Wiki_letter_w_cropped.svg/30px-Wiki_letter_w_cropped.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Wiki_letter_w_cropped.svg/40px-Wiki_letter_w_cropped.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="44" data-file-height="31" /></a></td>
<td class="mbox-text"><span class="mbox-text-span"><b>This section needs expansion</b>. <small>You can help by <a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Maserati&amp;action=edit&amp;section=">adding to it</a>.</small> <small><i>(September 2010)</i></small></span></td>
</tr>
</table>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Maserati_in_motorsport" title="Maserati in motorsport">Maserati in motorsport</a></div>
<p>Throughout its history, Maserati has participated in various forms of motorsports including <a href="/wiki/Formula_One" title="Formula One">Formula One</a>, <a href="/wiki/Sportscar_racing" class="mw-redirect" title="Sportscar racing">sportscar racing</a> and <a href="/wiki/Touring_car_racing" title="Touring car racing">touring car racing</a>, both as a works team and through private entrants.</p>
<p>Maserati developed fifteen GranTurismo MC racecars, homologated for the European Cup and National Endurance Series, one of which was raced by GT motorsport organization Cool Victory in Dubai in January, 2010.<sup id="cite_ref-duemotori.com_71-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-duemotori.com-71">[69]</a></sup></p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Notes">Notes</span></h2>
<div class="reflist" style="list-style-type: lower-alpha;">
<ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-10"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-10">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Near the town of Guidizzolo, a 4.2-litre Ferrari travelling at 250 km/h blew a tire and crashed into the roadside crowd, killing the driver, co-driver, and ten spectators, including five children. In response, <a href="/wiki/Enzo_Ferrari" title="Enzo Ferrari">Enzo Ferrari</a> was charged with manslaughter in a lengthy criminal prosecution that was finally dismissed in 1961.</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-22"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-22">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Gepi, or <i>Società per le Gestioni e Partecipazioni Industriali</i>, was a holding company owned by <a href="/wiki/Government-owned_corporation" class="mw-redirect" title="Government-owned corporation">state enterprises</a>, whose intended purpose was to assume control of privately owned companies in difficulty and to resell them once restructured. De Tomaso had carried out similar recovery operations with aid from Gepi in the previous years, notably for the <a href="/wiki/Benelli_(motorcycles)" title="Benelli (motorcycles)">Benelli</a> and <a href="/wiki/Moto_Guzzi" title="Moto Guzzi">Guzzi</a> <a href="/wiki/Motorcycle" title="Motorcycle">motorcycle</a> companies—which at the time he controlled.</span></li>
</ol>
</div>
